@node GMPM_Introduction "Introduction"

I know there are lots of Amiga musicians out there who where just
as I looking for some tool to access midi-parameters which can
not be accessed by the frontpanel of their (General Midi compa-
tible-) instrument. Those have to be controlled by some compu-
ter-program and of course a midi-interface.

After about four years snoopin' around on bulletin boards I only
found two PD-programs which were designed for this purpose!!
However, both of these programs would not suit my needs so I
decided to give it a try and program it myself. I have to state
that I am absolutely no programmer at all, so the program is not
totally bug-free (and certainly not fast) but I can work with it
now quite comfortably. It is written in HiSoft Basic, which I
got some time ago as a coverdisk to the Amiga Computing magazine.
As this is not the commercial version of HiSoft Basic you will
need the freely distributable HiSoftbasic.library (included) to
run the program.

This program is designed for the Roland E-35 keyboard, I don't know
if it's working on other GM-synth's!

IMPORTANT: This programs only works on a standard HIRES screen !!!
           (640 x 256 )

@endnode

@node GMPM_distribution "Distribution"

This archive contains all the files and libraries needed in order
to run the General Midi Patch Modifier. So if you'd like to install
the program on your harddisk you will have to place the accompanying
library-files in your DH0:LIBS drawer.

This program also uses the midi.library which means it will multi-
task with most other midi-programs (it is tested with AlgoRhythms
and Dr. T's KCS).

The distribution archive consists of the following files:

 - GMPM                            -  The program
 - GMPM.info
 - GMPM102.readme                  -  Short description
 - GMPM102.readme.info
 - GMPM.Guide                      -  This documentation
 - GMPM.Guide.info
 - LIBS:arp.library              |
 - LIBS:hisoftbasic.library      | -  The needed libraries
 - LIBS:mathieeedoubbas.library  |
 - LIBS:midi.library             |
 - CHN-Files:                  |
 - GMA-Files:                  |   -  The example directories
 - MID-Files:                  |

@endnode

@node GMPM_MainScreen "Main Screen"

The main (and only) screen consist of 12 sliders to edit various
controls. They are listed below:

Slider function        Accepted Value Range    Default Value     

Volume                     0-127                100
Program                    1-128                  1
Panpot                     0-127                 64
Modulation                 0-127                  0
Portamento time            0-127                  0
Pitchbend sensitivity      0-127                  2
Vibrato rate               0-127                 64     
Vibrato depth              0-127                 64     
Vibrato delay              0-127                 64     
Env. Attack time           0-127                 64
Env. Decay time            0-127                 64
Env. Release time          0-127                 64

The sliders are controlled by the mouse and directly influence
the sound on the active channel.

Note:

The portamento effect wil only work if you switch on portamento
from the @{"effects-menu" link GMPM_Effects}! 

On the top-right half of the program window you will see a copyright
notice and below that the name of the current program you are
editing.

On the bottom-right half you will find an overview of the current
settings of the other set of parameters which are accessible by
the menu's.

@endnode

@node GMPM_FileTypes "File types"

This program is channel-based. By this I mean that you first have
to select the channel to be edited from the menu 'Channel'. From
now on all your actions will only affect the chosen channel. When
you switch to another channel you will see that all values will
change to the values of the new chosen channel.

The program uses two kinds of file-types: .GMA and .CHN files.
These are the extensions created by the program. They stand for:

.GMA --> General Midi All channel file
.CHN --> Channel file

When you choose to save the current settings as a .GMA file you
will save all settings of all 16 channels.

When you choose to save the current settings as a .CHN file you
will save only the settings of the current channel.

The most important however is the possibility to save the settings
in standard midifile format (.MID), allowing you to import your
newly created sounds in your favourite sequencer program! This
was the one option I missed in the other available programs! 
Like with the .GMA and .CHN files it is possible to save all 16
channels (Standard Midi File format 1) or just the current channel
(Standard Midi File format 0).

The above mentioned load and save options are available by means
of the @{"Project menu" link GMPM_Project}.

@endnode


@node GMPM_Project "The Project menu"

'All channels default'   --> set all values in all channels to the
                             defaults as shown above.

'Current channel default'--> set all values in the current channel 
                             to the defaults as shown above.

'Unlock channel 10'      --> channel 10 is mostly used as the drums
                             channel, so this option is meant to
                             protect the settings of channel 10.
                             This is a toggle switch.

'Panic'                  --> When your experiments are out of
                             control use this to silence the active
                             channel.

'Quit'                   --> This is a funny option, I should have
                             left it out...

@endnode

@node GMPM_Effects "The Effects menu"

The next menu is the 'Effects' menu. These are four toggle switches
to activate or de-activate the Hold, Soft, Sostenuto and Portamento
functions.

@endnode

@node GMPM_Bank "The Bank menu"

The next menu 'Bank' might not be of use for some of you. When
you own a Roland E-series keyboard it will probably work. I don't
know how other instruments will react on it. These are also toggle
switches.

@endnode

@node GMPM_Channel "The Channel menu"

Then there is the 'Channel' menu. Just select the channel you
want to work with, that's all. You will see that at startup channel
10 is 'ghosted'. This means channel 10 is 'locked'. You can 'un-
lock' it from the @{"projects menu" link GMPM_Project}.

@endnode

@node GMPM_Misc "The Misc. menu"

In the 'Misc.' menu there are 4 more parameters to edit. Instead
of sliders you here have to type in the values for Reverb depth,
Chorus depth, TVF-Cutoff and TVF-resonance.

Also here are the possibilities of swapping or copying channels. 

@endnode

@node GMPM_Midi "The Send MIDI menu"
 
The last menu 'Send MIDI' does exactly as it says, it sends all
current settings to your midi-instrument. You can choose to send
all the data of all channels or just the data of the current
channel. In fact you should not have to use this option very
often as every change of a parameter will be directly send to
your instrument!

@endnode

@node GMPM_Author "The Author"

Well, thats all about it and it's final. I won't develop this
program any further. To me it was just for fun.

I hope you will enjoy this program as much as I did in making it.

If you want to contact me (not about updates, because there won't
be any!) or if you want to send me a similar program (I hope which does
the job much better!) or other usefull PD-miditools you're welcome.
Of course I would like to receive your reactions on this program and
hear from you if you're a Roland E-35 (or other E-series) user!!!

Please e-mail to: ronver@bos.nl  
                  (Ronald Vermeulen)

@endnode

